<paragraph blockId="19.[189,1399,451,655]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
The female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kuhlmann" authorityName="Kuhlmann" box="[364,668,451,477]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oubergensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[364,536,451,477]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">S. oubergensis</emphasis>
Kuhlmann
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[676,768,452,478]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be separated from all other species of this group by the combination of the following characters: supraclypeal area and clypeus coarsely and densely punctate and shiny, only partly superficially sculptured and slightly matt (
<figureCitation box="[1050,1142,522,548]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,523,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[189,1399,523,1894]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 9. Scrapter oubergensis Kuhlmann sp. nov., ♀, holotype (RCMK). A. Lateral view. B. Head. C. Scutum and scutellum (dorsal view). D. Metanotum and propodeum (dorsal view). E. Metasoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836070/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
); scutum coarsely but relatively densely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[526,621,558,584]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,523,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[189,1399,523,1894]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 9. Scrapter oubergensis Kuhlmann sp. nov., ♀, holotype (RCMK). A. Lateral view. B. Head. C. Scutum and scutellum (dorsal view). D. Metanotum and propodeum (dorsal view). E. Metasoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836070/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
); basal area of propodeum medially about as long as metanotum (
<figureCitation box="[198,294,593,619]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,523,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[189,1399,523,1894]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 9. Scrapter oubergensis Kuhlmann sp. nov., ♀, holotype (RCMK). A. Lateral view. B. Head. C. Scutum and scutellum (dorsal view). D. Metanotum and propodeum (dorsal view). E. Metasoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836070/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9D</figureCitation>
); stigma brown; apical margins of metasomal terga black; terga densely and finely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[198,289,629,655]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="20.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,523,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[189,1399,523,1894]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Fig. 9. Scrapter oubergensis Kuhlmann sp. nov., ♀, holotype (RCMK). A. Lateral view. B. Head. C. Scutum and scutellum (dorsal view). D. Metanotum and propodeum (dorsal view). E. Metasoma (dorsal view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3836070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3836070/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 9E</figureCitation>
). The male is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
